Lab 8.3.1: Fitting Classification Trees

Working through fitting classification trees

#install.packages("tree")
library(tree)
library(ISLR)
attach(Carseats)

High = ifelse(Sales <= 8, "No", "Yes")

Carseats = data.frame(Carseats, High)

Now, using tree() to fit classification tree for predicting “High” status 

tree.carseats = tree(High~.-Sales, Carseats)
summary(tree.carseats)
## 
## Classification tree:
## tree(formula = High ~ . - Sales, data = Carseats)
## Variables actually used in tree construction:
## [1] "ShelveLoc"   "Price"       "Income"      "CompPrice"   "Population" 
## [6] "Advertising" "Age"         "US"         
## Number of terminal nodes:  27 
## Residual mean deviance:  0.4575 = 170.7 / 373 
## Misclassification error rate: 0.09 = 36 / 400
plot(tree.carseats)
text(tree.carseats, pretty = 0)

Creating the test/train sets

set.seed(2)
train = sample(1:nrow(Carseats),200)

Carseats.test = Carseats[-train,]

High.test= High[-train]

tree.carseats = tree(High~.-Sales, Carseats, subset = train)

tree.pred = predict(tree.carseats, Carseats.test, type = "class")

table(tree.pred,High.test)
##          High.test
## tree.pred No Yes
##       No  86  27
##       Yes 30  57
cat("Success rate of: ",(86+57)/(86+57+27+30)*100)
## Success rate of:  71.5

Pruning Classification Trees: The act of removing sectinos of the tree with little classification power

We’ll first cross-validate to check for the optimal sizes

  • Because at size 9, there is an error-rate of only 50 (the minimum), we should reduce to a 9-node tree

below: dev corresponds to the cross-validation error rate

set.seed(3)

cv.carseats = cv.tree(tree.carseats, FUN = prune.misclass)

names(cv.carseats)
## [1] "size"   "dev"    "k"      "method"
cv.carseats
## $size
## [1] 19 17 14 13  9  7  3  2  1
## 
## $dev
## [1] 55 55 53 52 50 56 69 65 80
## 
## $k
## [1]       -Inf  0.0000000  0.6666667  1.0000000  1.7500000  2.0000000
## [7]  4.2500000  5.0000000 23.0000000
## 
## $method
## [1] "misclass"
## 
## attr(,"class")
## [1] "prune"         "tree.sequence"
par(mfrow = c(1,2))

plot(cv.carseats$size, cv.carseats$dev, type="b")
plot(cv.carseats$k, cv.carseats$dev, type="b")

Now, we want to obtain the reduced tree using pruning

prune.carseats = prune.misclass(tree.carseats,best = 9)

plot(prune.carseats)
text(prune.carseats,pretty = 0)

Checking to see how good the pruning method works on test data 

tree.pred=predict(prune.carseats,Carseats.test, type = "class")

table(tree.pred, High.test)
##          High.test
## tree.pred No Yes
##       No  94  24
##       Yes 22  60
cat("Success rate of: ",(94+60)/(96+60+22+24))
## Success rate of:  0.7623762

As is indicated, our accuracy with prediction/classification has gone up

Increasing the size of the tree reduces the accuracy:

prune.carseats = prune.misclass(tree.carseats,best = 15)

plot(prune.carseats)
text(prune.carseats,pretty = 0)

tree.pred=predict(prune.carseats,Carseats.test, type = "class")

table(tree.pred, High.test)
##          High.test
## tree.pred No Yes
##       No  86  22
##       Yes 30  62
cat("Success rate of: ",(86+62)/(200))
## Success rate of:  0.74

Lab 8.3.2: Fitting Regression Trees

set.seed(1)

Pruning

I’m not entirely sure why the lab in instructs us to prune the tree into a 5-node tree when it’s evident that a 7-node tree yields the least amount of errors.

prune.boston = prune.tree(tree.boston,best=5)
plot(prune.boston)
text(prune.boston,pretty = 0)

Testing

yhat = predict(tree.boston, newdata = Boston[-train,])
boston.test = Boston[-train, "medv"]
plot(yhat, boston.test)
abline(0,1)

mean((yhat-boston.test)^2)
## [1] 25.04559
